Linear Regression - Practicals

Short practicals

In this short practicals, we will show for linear regression model how to perform

  • estimation
  • inference
  • prediction and
  • model checking

As pre-requisites, make sure you have

  • created a new project
  • placed the dataset inside the project directory

Then, load the required R libraries

Estimation

This is to estimate a constant only model (model with only the dependent variable).

Multivariable model with no interaction

Now, we lets estimate a multivariable model, thats a model with

  • One dependent variable (hba1c)
  • two or more covariates.

In this example, we will use ldl and gender as covariates

modldl.gender <- lm(hba1c ~ ldl + gender, data = data0)
summary(modldl.gender)

Multivariable with interaction

Now, we will add a new covariate (an interaction term) which is the product of two covariates

  • dependent variable (hba1c)
  • covariates ldl and gender (ldl + gender)
  • interaction covariate: (ldl*gender)
modldl.gender.ia <- lm(hba1c ~ ldl + gender + ldl:gender, 
                       data = data0)
summary(modldl.gender.ia)
## 
## Call:

Inference

For inference, we will calculate the \(95\%\) for the \(\hat{\beta}\) . We can produce nicer results with broom::tidy()

tidy(modldl, conf.int = TRUE)
tidy(modldl.gender, conf.int = TRUE)
tidy(modldl.gender.ia)

Prediction

Now, we can get the fitted values for hba1c thats the average values of the dependent variable given the covariates values

augment(modldl) %>% head()
augment(modldl.gender.ia) %>% tail()

Model checking

Linear regression requires linear model assumptions. Some important assumptions are

  1. Linearity of residuals
  2. Residuals are normally distributed
  3. Equal variance of residuals
  4. Independence observations

Lets make some plot to help us with model checking. See @ref(fig:assessplot) )

plot(modldl)

plot(modldl.gender.ia)

What do you think of the plots?

Somethings are not right

  • distribution of residuals do not look random
  • possible outliers

However, the linearity maybe acceptable.

We need to do further treatment to improve our model. Some treatments include

  • transformation of variables
  • using more complex model
  • removing the outliers or influential observations

Long practicals

Preparation

Set a new project in RStudio (recommended) or set a working directory. To set the new project, click

File -> New Project -> New Directory -> New Project

You need to know the file path. It is treated differently in Windows OS, Linux OS and Mac OD.

In the project, you should store your dataset and your R codes (with or without folders) inside the folder of the project directory. The directory will later save the objects and outputs such as plots.

Load R packages

You can load R packages that you want to use for the analysis. In this project we load

  1. tidyverse - for data wrangling and plots
  2. haven - to read data
  3. gtsummary - to summarize data
  4. corrplot- to make plot for correlation
  5. knitr - to make nice table
  6. broom - to create nice outputs
  7. MASS - to do variable selection
  8. tidyr - to use drop_na
library(tidyverse) 
library(gtsummary)
## #BlackLivesMatter
library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.92 loaded
library(broom)
library(tidyr)

Read data

To read .csv, .txt files, you can use base package. But to read statistical data from SPSS (.sav), Stata (.dta) or spreadsheet such .xlsx file you need user-contributed packages such as haven, foreign, readr or readxl.

Please note that, haven can read up to the latest STATA format while foreign reads until version 12.

data1 <- read_dta(here('datamssm_a.dta'))

Explore and wrangle data

Perform plots, to look for

  1. outliers
  2. range of data
  3. missing data
  4. error in data entry
  5. wrong groupings
  6. distribution of data
ggplot(data1, aes(hba1c)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_grid(dmdx~.) 

ggplot(data1, aes(fbs)) + 
  geom_histogram() + 
  facet_grid(dmdx~.)

  geom_histogram()

We may want to

  1. remove hba1c less than 2.5
  2. remove ldl less than 0.5 mmol/l
  3. remove total cholesterol less than 2.0 mmol/l
  4. remove ftrigliz less than 2 mmol/l or higher than 10 mmol/l
  5. remove mdbpr less than 40
  6. generate bmi
data2 <- 
  data1 %>% 
  filter(hba1c > 2.5, ldl > 0.5, totchol >=2.0, ftrigliz < 8, mdbpr >=40) %>% 
  mutate(bmi = weight/(height^2)) %>% 
  mutate(overweight = if_else(bmi >=25.0,'overwt','not_overwt'))

Multivariable model

In multivariable analysis, there will be at least 2 covariates. Let us say we would like to model hba1c with these covariate age and fbs. In multivariable analysis, we can:

  1. estimate the effect of age adjusted for fbs
  2. estimate the effet of fbs when age is controlled
  3. predict the average hba1c value for a given value of age and fbs
mod.age.fbs <- lm(hba1c ~ age + fbs, data = data2)
summary(mod.age.fbs)

Next, lets model hba1c with these covariates: age, fbs, overweight (overwt vs not_overwt).

In multivariable analysis, we can:

  1. estimate the effect of age adjusted for fbs and hpt status
  2. estimate the effet of fbs when age and hpt status are controlled
  3. predict the average hba1c for a given value of age, fbs and hpt status
mod.age.fbs.ow <- lm(hba1c ~ age + fbs + overweight, data = data2)
tidy(mod.age.fbs.ow, conf.int = TRUE)

Model comparison

You can compare by

  1. doing the anova test between models
  2. looking at p-value for each covariate (not advisable)

Between mod.age.fbs.ow and mod.age.fbs but different sample size will not allow anova() to work. So, we will use remove NA values from our data to ensure equal sample size.

# anova(mod.age, mod.age.fbs,na.action = na.omit) # does not work
data2.compl <- data2 %>% 
  filter(!is.na(age), 
         !is.na(fbs), 
         !is.na(overweight))

Now, let us compare again

mod.age.fbs.ow.ss <- lm(hba1c ~ age + fbs + overweight, data = data2.compl)
mod.age.fbs.ss <- lm(hba1c ~ age + fbs, data = data2.compl)
anova(mod.age.fbs.ow.ss, mod.age.fbs.ss)

There is significant (p-value < 0.05) difference between the two models. What do you think of the contribution of overweight to the model?

Model selection

We now build a model using stepwise variable selection

For both and forward, we need to remove missing (NA) values. Note: Do not load MASS package before using dplyr::select(). They conflict with one another

data2.complete <- 
  data2 %>% 
  dplyr::select(hba1c, age,fbs, overweight, gender, 
         crural, height, weight, waist, 
         msbpr,mdbpr, hdl, ldl) %>% 
         drop_na()

Start with the easiest : backward selection

Of course, model selection is not as easy as running automatic selection (forward, backward, stepwise).

WARNING Do not let automatic variable selection fools you when your main interest is explaining the role of covariates and not prediction.

  1. age
  2. fbs

  4. crural

Handling Confounding

SBP and DBP are variables that have strong relationship between them. Hence, in our data, msbpr and mdbpr are highly correlated.

Examine, what will happen

  1. if the model has only msbpr as covariate
  2. if the model has only mdbpr as covariate
  3. if the model has both msbpr and mdbpr as covariates
data2 %>%
  ggplot(aes(msbpr, mdbpr)) + geom_point() +
   stat_smooth(method = "lm", col = "red")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Model with sbp (model 1)

mod.sbp <- lm(hba1c ~ msbpr , data = data2)
mod.sbp.res <- tidy(mod.sbp)
mod.sbp.res

Model with dbp (model 2)

mod.dbp <- lm(hba1c ~ mdbpr , data = data2)
mod.dbp.res <- tidy(mod.dbp)
mod.dbp.res

Now, what happens when we add sbp and dbp (model 3)?

mod.sbp.dbp <- lm(hba1c ~ msbpr + mdbpr, data = data2)
mod.sbp.dbp.res <- tidy(mod.sbp.dbp)
mod.sbp.dbp.res

Identifying Interaction

Numerical and numerical covariates

For example, a model with no interaction between fbs and bmi

mod.fbs.bmi <- lm(hba1c ~ fbs + bmi, data = data2)
tidy(mod.fbs.bmi)

For example, a model with an interaction between fbs and bmi

int.fbs.bmi <- lm(hba1c ~ fbs + bmi + fbs:bmi, data = data2)
tidy(int.fbs.bmi)

Lets compare between the two models and see if adding an interaction will significantly improve the model.

anova(int.fbs.bmi, mod.fbs.bmi)

The models are different based on anova test with a significant at level of 5 percent (p < 0.0029)

Numerical and categorical covariate

A model with covariates fbs and overweight

mod.fbs.ow <- lm(hba1c ~ fbs + overweight, data = data2)
tidy(mod.fbs.ow)

A model with covariates fbs and overweight and interaction between them

int.fbs.ow <-lm(hba1c ~ fbs + overweight + fbs:overweight, data = data2)
tidy(int.fbs.ow)

It is difficult to assess when you have multiple p-values. anova can help to see overall if there is difference between models.

anova(mod.fbs.ow, int.fbs.ow)

Let us take model with covariates fbs, overweight, crural, the interaction between fbs and overweight, msbpr, ldl and gender as our potential final model. This is known as the preliminary final model

                       msbpr + ldl + gender, data = data2)

Fitted values, residuals and influential values

Even though, R can produce automatically some plots that you can use to assess the model, it is better if you can do the plots on your own.

Steps:

  1. Generate the fitted value
  2. Generate the residuals
  3. Generate the influential values

Based on the values above, you

  • make some plots to check assumptions
  • generate some diagnostic values to assess the outliers and find influential observations
res.mod <- residuals(prelim.final.m)
head(res.mod)

library(DT)

data2.pred.res <- augment(prelim.final.m)
data2.pred.res %>% datatable()

Predictions

To generate the predicted values based on current data, use the broom::augment() function.

If based on new data, then create new data first. To do that, we need to detach the MASS package we used before.

  • Generate new data
new_data <- expand.grid(fbs = c(5.0, 11.0), 
                        overweight = c('overwt', 'not_overwt'),
                        crural = c('urban','rural'),
                        msbpr = mean(data2$msbpr),
                        ldl = mean(data2$ldl),
                        gender = c('female','male'))
new_data

Now, we can predict the average hba1c for the new data we created just now

pred.hba1c <- augment(prelim.final.m, newdata = new_data)
pred.hba1c %>% datatable()

Influentials

  1. Cooks distance : values above 1 or above \(\frac{4}{n}\)
  2. standardized residuals : values above 2 or lower than \(-2\)
  3. leverage above \(\frac{2k + 2}{n}\) = \(\frac{2(7) + 2}{4225} = 0.0038\)

Any observation for which the Cooks distance is close to 1 or more, or that is substantially larger than other Cooks distances (highly influential data points), requires investigation. Good reference (here)[https://ademos.people.uic.edu/Chapter12.html#32_testing_for_outliers:_outliertest()]

cutoff <- 4/((nrow(data2)-length(prelim.final.m$coefficients)-2))
plot(prelim.final.m, which = 4, cook.levels = cutoff)

data2.pred.res %>% 
  filter(.std.resid > 2 | .std.resid < -2 | .hat > 0.0038) %>%
  datatable()

Now lets keep standardized residuals between 2 and -2

non.influen.obs <- 
  data2.pred.res %>% 
  filter(.std.resid < 2 & .std.resid > -2 & .hat < 0.0038)

Run the model again

prelim.final.m2 <- lm(hba1c ~ fbs + overweight + crural + fbs*overweight +
                       msbpr + ldl + gender, data = non.influen.obs)

Run diagnostics

plot(prelim.final.m2)
